                        <additions>
                            <lb/>
                            <label rend="bold">Inscriptions:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a"
                                >1a:</locus> bears the title and author in Persian:<lb/>
                            <q xml:lang="fa">نسخه مطد المدام فی شدح قصیره طپد الکلام تصنیف سید انشاٰ
                                الله خان متخلص انشا ابن حکیم مید ماشاء الله حسینی نجفی جعفری نبشته
                                [نوشته] سنه ۱۲۳۳ هجری </q><lb/>
                            <locus from="2a" to="2a">Folio 2a:</locus> bears a short variant title
                            and author's name in Persian:<lb/> شرح قصیده بی نقاط تصنیف انشأ الله خان <lb/>
                            <label rend="bold">Bookplates:</label>
                            <locus from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">Left
                                doublure</locus>, <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with
                            shelf mark <q xml:lang="en">1/H</q>, and <q xml:lang="en"><hi
                                    rend="strikethrough">Hamilton</hi> MSS No. <hi
                                    rend="strikethrough">533</hi></q> with the name and number
                            crossed out, and <q>Persian</q> and <q>616</q> written aside. </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding notBefore="1861" notAfter="1865">
                                <p>Probably rebound in a hybrid British-Indian style in <placeName
                                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535"
                                        key="place_7001535">Dehli</placeName> for former owner
                                        <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo"
                                        change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William
                                        Hamilton</persName>.</p>
                                <p>Repaired, mould-made laid endpapers added to the beginning and
                                    end, with 11 laid lines per 20 mm and 26 mm between chain lines.
                                    Resewn at three stations, unsupported. Edges trimmed and chevron
                                    endbands of white and black threads twined at <locus from="Head"
                                        to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail"
                                        >tail</locus>. Covered in full claret-coloured polished
                                    goatskin <material>leather</material> over
                                        <material>pasteboards</material> with squares along the
                                    edges and defined joints but without a flap (Type III binding as
                                    per Déroche), with interior doublures British made
                                    shell-patterned marbled papers, with their excess widths put
                                    down as hinges to connect the cover to the textblock.</p>
                                <decoNote type="binding"><locus from="Spine" to="Spine"
                                        >Spine</locus> bore a label, now missing. Board margins and
                                    spine dyed black, outlined with double ruled yellow lines, with
                                    interior single-ruled margins of the same.</decoNote>
                                <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                                        <height>224</height>
                                        <width>163</width>
                                        <depth>35</depth>
                                    </dimensions></p>
                                <condition>Binding in fair but stable condition, with boards yawning
                                    at the fore-edge, head and tail caps cracked, minor scuffing to the exterior, and loose
                                    sewing.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>Possibly completed by the author <persName role="scr" cert="medium"
                                    xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Abū-al-Barakāt bin Muḥammd Naṣr
                                    Allāh</persName> on behalf of <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"
                                    >Mīr Sayyid Iltifāt</persName> in <origPlace cert="medium"
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502">Awadh</origPlace>
                                in regnal year 23 of Shāh ‘Ālam, corresponding to <origDate
                                    calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1747-08-17">7 Sha‘bān 1160 (17
                                    Aug 1747)</origDate>.</p></origin>
                        <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied"
                                    key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel
                                    George William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> who served in
                                    <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                                    key="place_7000208">India</placeName>
                                <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to
                                    1867</date>, latterly as Commissioner in <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535"
                                    key="place_7001535">Delhi</placeName>. He acquired over a
                                thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts, from which the <orgName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252">British Museum</orgName>
                                purchased 352 from his widow, <persName key="person_f8470"
                                    role="fmo">Charlotte Logie Hamilton (1817–1893)</persName>, now
                                held in the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British
                                    Library</orgName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance><p>
                                <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">
                                    Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName>,
                                purchased the remainder in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868"
                                    >1868</date> for <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552"
                                    key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh
                                Hall, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384"
                                    key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                                    change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName>
                                in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from
                                    <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                                    key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                    Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup"
                                    >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                                    type="corporation" role="rps"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                                    Library</orgName>, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                                    key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
